@node intro "Introduction"
It  all began when I tried to print an AmigaGuide® file. As everyone knows,
an  AmigaGuide®  file is divided into nodes, which are not displayed all at
the  same time. They are linked together via links (surprise!) and the user
is able to jump from one node to another by clicking on those links.

Such  a  structure  is  great  for  displaying a doc file on screen, but it
becomes  quite  strange when sent to a printer, as all AmigaGuide® commands
which are normally hidden become visible.

I  then  thought of clearing by hand all those AmigaGuide® commands, and to
copy the contents of each node into a plain text file, with the help of the
clipboard. But it was quite unhandy and became very long for large guides.

So  I thought of a program to do the job. As ARexx  has handy functions for
manipulating  strings and was easy to use, it was the best choice for quick
development.  Then I thought "why dropping such lovely AmigaGuide® commands
that  could  be  used  to enhance the printing of the file?". So I chose to
convert the file to TeX format instead of plain ASCII text.

The  tool  texinfo  already exists that can output (among other things like
html)  AmigaGuide®  files and DVI files, but requires the author writes the
documentation  in  an even higher language. Programs you can find on Aminet
(or  elsewhere) generally only provide the AmigaGuide® documentation files.
Anyway,  AmigaGuide® files produced by texinfo are generally converted very
well by GuideToTeX.

For  those  who don't know TeX, it is a portable typesetting system that is
universally  used  for  its  high-quality  typesetting  (thanks  to  clever
algorithms  and vector fonts) and excellent handling of mathematics. TeX is
not  a WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) system, it is a language: you
first  type a "source" document (an ASCII file that contains many commands,
beginning  with  a  "\\") and then process it through TeX to produce a "dvi"
(device  independent)  file,  which  can  then  be  displayed  on screen or
printed.

The  best  implementation  of TeX on the Amiga (and the most up-to-date) is
currently AmiWeb2c, by Andreas Scherer (who did the conversion from Unix to
AmigaOS).  It  uses parts of PasTeX, the first public domain implementation
of  TeX  on  the  Amiga.  Aminet contains a whole directory for TeX-related
files ("text/tex").

So  I  wrote  GuideToTeX as an ARexx program. Needless to say that my first
thoughts  of  an  "easy  job  of 1 hour" proved wrong. Indeed, many special
cases  were  to  be  taken  into  account,  as  to  links,  styles, escaped
characters,  translating  characters  to  TeX format... Anyway, here it is.
It's  not  perfect  (see @{"problems" link probs}) but it proved useful although the output
file may require a bit of editing for top typesetting.

For an example of what it can do, see the @{"GuideToTeX.guide.dvi" system "ShowDVI GuideToTeX.guide.dvi"} file, it was
produced from this file with very few editing.

Now, the GuideToTeX package has been divided in several parts. The heart of
the  system  is  the  @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex}  ARexx  script,  which  does  all the
conversion  stuff.  The  program  @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi}  adds  more  features and
options  at a higher level. And there are a number (well currently 1 :-) of
@{"header  files" link provheaders} for some adjustments. With a bit of experience, I am sure you
will find this system quite powerful. Don't forget to tell me about it!

@endnode

@node sysreq "System requirements"
GuideToTeX requires:

-- An Amiga (or maybe UAE)

-- Version  2.04  or  higher of the AmigaOS is maybe  necessary. I strongly
suggest version 3.1 or higher.

-- ARexx running (make sure RexxMast is started in your startup-sequence or
user-startup).

-- rexxdossupport.library  ©1994-1997   Hartmut  Goebel   (the  archive  is
provided).

-- AmigaGuide® files to convert :-)

-- a TeX package will be necessary for typesetting the resulting TeX files.
Search for "AmiWeb2C" on Aminet.

-- a bit of knowledge and TeXnique may be required to adjust the results.

--  if  you  want  to  use the graphical interface GuideToDVI-GUI, you need
Argue  version  0.9  or  higher. It is a MUI interface systems for programs
using  ReadArgs().  You  will  find  it  on  Aminet.  Argue was written and
copyrighted by Thorsten "Flavour" Stocksmeier.
@endnode

@node guidetotex "GuideToTeX.rexx"
GuideToTeX.rexx  is  the  script  the  GuideToTeX package is based upon. It
takes  care  of  the conversion of most AmigaGuide® commands into their TeX
"equivalents".  Several  other  scripts  call  GuideToTeX.rexx  but provide
higher level options.

From the shell, usage is as follows:

rx GuideToTeX.rexx GUIDEFILE/A, PRE= PREINCLUDE/K, POST= POSTINCLUDE/K,
LINKTOKENS/K, NODETOKENS/K, ENDNODETOKENS/K, B=BOLD/K, UB= UNBOLD/K, I=
ITALIC/K, UI= UNITALIC/K, U= UNDERLINE/K, UU= UNUNDERLINE/K,
SPACEINDENT/K/N, TABINDENT/K/N, RUNTEX/K, NOACCENTS/S, ONLYNODES/S,
BLS=BLANKLINESKIP/K, LOGFILE/K, QUIET/S

For  those who are not familiar with the syntax of the ReadArgs() function,
read @{"here" link readargs} for the meaning of the /<letter>:

@{b}GUIDEFILE@{ub}  :  (required)  the  name  of the guide file to be converted. The
output file will be the same but with a ".tex" extension.

@{b}PRE=PREINCLUDE@{ub}  :  The name of a TeX file to be included before any text is
processed.  This  should  include  font  definitions  and any special macro
needed  for  LINKTOKENS  or  NODETOKENS,  and  any  text  needed before the
contents of the guide are included. Default is no file.

@{b}POST=POSTINCLUDE@{ub} : The name of a TeX file to be included after all the text
in the guide file has been processed. Default is no file.

@{b}LINKTOKENS@{ub}  : The tokens to include when a link is encountered in the file.
For  example, if LINKTOKENS is set to "{\\bf %s}" then the links will appear
in bold. The default is "\\underbar{%s}" which will underline the links. The
"%s" denotes where the link text will be placed.

@{b}NODETOKENS@{ub}  :  The  tokens  to include when a new node is encountered. Then
"%s"  denotes  the title of the node (defaults to the node name if there is
no  title to the node) and %d denotes the number of the node (starting from
1).  This can be used to build section titles as: "\\vskip 1cm {\\headingfont
%d.--- %s}". Use NODETOKENS="" if you don't want the titles. You could also
use   a   page   jump   (\\vfill\\eject).   The   default   is  "{\\bf  %d.---
%s}\\medskip\\nobreak"  which  causes  a  the  number  and  title of the node
separated  by  an  em  dash and printed in bold, and a medium skip, with no
page break.

@{b}ENDNODETOKENS@{ub} : The tokens to include when an end of node is reached. These
are  inserted  "as  is",  i.e.  no  "%s"  stuff  is  done.  The  default is
"\smallskip\hrule\goodbreak\bigskip":  a  vertical  skip,  horizontal rule,
indication of a possible page break and another vertical blank.

@{b}B=BOLD@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command \@{b} will translate to this. Default: \\bf{}.

@{b}UB=UNBOLD@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command  \@{ub} will translate to this. Default: \\rm{}.

@{b}I=ITALIC@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command \@{i} will translate to this. Default: \\it{}.

@{b}UI=UNITALIC@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command \@{ui} will translate to this. Default: \\rm{}.

@{b}U=UNDERLINE@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command \@{u} will translate to this. Default: \\tt{}.

@{b}UU=UNUNDERLINE@{ub} : The AmigaGuide command \@{uu} will translate to this. Default: \\rm{}.

@{b}SPACEINDENT@{ub} : If a line is indented with spaces, the spaces are replaced by
a  \\hskip causing a horizontal blank. The amount of that skip is the number
of spaces indenting the line times the value expressed here in millimeters.
The default is 2 millimeters.

@{b}TABINDENT@{ub}  :  If a line is indented with tabulators, they are replaced by a
\\hskip causing a horizontal blank. The amount of that skip is the number of
tabulators   indenting   the   line  times  the  value  expressed  here  in
millimeters. The default is 16 millimeters, causing the (default) tabulator
to be equivalent to eight (default) spaces.

@{b}RUNTEX@{ub}  :  If  this  argument  is not empty (default) then it is used as an
invocation  command for typesetting. Suggested is simply "tex %s". The "%s"
will of course be replaced by the destination file name.

@{b}NOACCENTS@{ub}  :  If  you  know  your  guide  file  does  not  contain accented
characters,  or  if you use a eight-bit version of TeX, you can disable the
conversion  of  accented  (and other) characters (ŕ,é,č,Ń,×,etc.) with this
switch. This will speed up the conversion.

@{b}ONLYNODES@{ub}  : Normally, text which happens not to be in a node (ie between a
\@node/\@endnode  pair) is processed all the same, although it is not visible
in the guide. With this switch set, GuideToTeX will ignore such text.

@{b}BLS=BLANKLINESKIP@{ub}  :  If  a blank line is detected, this macro is inserted.
This  is  by  default  "\\medskip"  but  you can change it as you wish. Note
however  that a blank line also implies the end of a paragraph and that TeX
then  adds the \\parskip vertical blank before the new paragraph. This macro
is  useful if a paragraph is started by TeX because of an indented line but
no blank line in the guide: this macro is NOT included in that case.

@{b}LOGFILE@{ub}  :  Name of a file which will contain all outputs of GuideToTeX. It
is not affected by the QUIET option. Default: "GuideToTeX.log".

@{b}QUIET@{ub} : Only display error messages.

Don't forget to read about the @{"problems" link "probs"}!
@endnode

@node guidetodvi "GuideToDVI.rexx"
GuideToDVI.rexx  is  a script that uses GuideToTeX.rexx but provides higher
level  options  for  the  conversion. Basically, GuideToDVI.rexx prepares a
temporary  file  containing useful macro definitions and tokens definitions
used  for  the  conversion,  along  with some adjustments for a better page
layout.

GuideToDVI.rexx is used from the shell and called like this:

rx GuideToDVI.rexx GUIDEFILE/A, CONFIG/K, MAGNIFICATION/K/N, HSIZE/K/N,
VSIZE/K/N, HOFFSET/K/N, VOFFSET/K/N, BLACKBOXES/S, PARINDENT/K/N, FRENCH/S,
TPH= TITLEPAGEHEAD/K, TPF= TITLEPAGEFOOT/K, LPH= LEFTPAGEHEAD/K, LPF=
LEFTPAGEFOOT/K, RPH= RIGHTPAGEHEAD/K, RPF= RIGHTPAGEFOOT/K, PRE=
PREINCLUDE/K, POST= POSTINCLUDE/K, LOGFILE/K, QUIET/S

All  those arguments can also be filled via a MUI GUI by double-clicking on
GuideToDVI-GUI. You @{"need" link sysreq} Argue for this.

For  those who are not familiar with the syntax of the ReadArgs() function,
read @{"here" link readargs} for the meaning of the /<letter>:

Before  going  on  with the description of each argument, note that each of
these  can  also  be found in a configuration file (specified by the @{b}CONFIG@{ub}
keyword). Arguments on the command line override those in the configuration
file. The default configuration file is @{i}"TEX:config/GuideToDVI.config"@{ui}.

@{b}GUIDEFILE@{ub} : (required) the name of the guide file to be converted.

@{b}CONFIGFILE @{ub} :  name of a config file to read. Config files contain the same
commands, except for @{b}GUIDEFILE@{ub}. Default: "TEX:config/GuideToDVI.config".

@{b}MAGNIFICATION@{ub} : magnification factor for the document. Default: 0.

@{b}HSIZE@{ub} : page width, in centimeters. Default: 16.

@{b}VSIZE@{ub} : page height, in centimeters. Default: 24.

@{b}HOFFSET@{ub} : text horizontal offset in the page, in millimeters. Default:0.

@{b}VOFFSET@{ub} : text vertical offset in the page, in millimeters. Default:0.

@{b}BLACKBOXES@{ub} : (use BLACKBOXES on|off). Enables or disables TeX's black boxes
in the right margin where there are overfull \\hboxes. Default: off.

@{b}PARINDENT@{ub} : Paragraph indention, in millimeters. Default: 0.

@{b}FRENCH@{ub}  :  Toggles  the  french  style. This implies \\frenchspacing and the
redefinition of punctuation signs to take into account the french rules for
those. Default: off.

@{b}TPH=TITLEPAGEHEAD@{ub}  : The tokens to insert in the headline of the title page
(normally the first page of the document). Default: "{\\hfil}".

@{b}TPF=TITLEPAGEFOOT@{ub}  : The tokens to insert in the footline of the title page
(normally the first page of the document). Default: "{\\hfil}".

@{b}LPH=LEFTPAGEHEAD@{ub}  : The tokens to insert in the headline of the left (even)
page. Default: "{\\hfil\\tenrm\\the\\databasename/\\the\\currentnodetitle\\hfil}".

@{b}LPF=LEFTPAGEFOOT@{ub}  : The tokens to insert in the footline of the left (even)
page. Default: "{\\hfil\\tenrm\\folio\\hfil}".

@{b}RPH=RIGHTPAGEHEAD@{ub} : The tokens to insert in the headline of the right (odd)
page. Default: same as @{b}LPH@{ub}.

@{b}RPF=RIGHTPAGEFOOT@{ub} : The tokens to insert in the footline of the right (odd)
page. Default: same as @{b}LPF@{ub}.

@{b}PRE=PREINCLUDE@{ub}  :  Name of a TeX file to be included before the text of the
guide. Default: "" (none).

@{b}POST=POSTINCLUDE@{ub}  : Name of a TeX file to be included after the text of the
guide. Default: "" (none).

@{b}LOGFILE@{ub}  :  Name of a file which will contain all outputs of GuideToDVI. It
is not affected by the QUIET option. Default: "GuideToDVI.log".

@{b}QUIET@{ub}  :  only display error messages. It implies QUIET for @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex}
too.

After  processing by GuideToDVI.rexx, the file is processed through TeX via
the command @{i}tex %s@{ui} (%s is replaced by the converted file name).


You  need some TeX knowledge to modify the following values and macros. The
default settings should be OK for the novice user.

Some  special tokens or counters are defined (in the temporary file created
by GuideToDVI) and can safely be used in a redefinition of the @{b}\\link@{ub}, @{b}\\node@{ub}
or  @{b}\\endnode@{ub} macros (read on for more about these), or used in a @{b}PREINCLUDE@{ub}
or  @{b}POSTINCLUDE@{ub} file. They are NOT macros themselves, you must use  \\the to
include them in the text.

@{b}\\databasename@{ub}  :  Name  of the database (after the \@database keyword at the
begining of the guide).

@{b}\\guidefilename@{ub}   :   Name   of   the  guide  file.  This  can  differ  from
@{b}\\databasename@{ub}, of course. Only the file component of the path.

@{b}\\guidedirname@{ub}  :  Name  of the directory containing the guide file. This is
NOT an absolute path, rather the path component of the @{b}GUIDEFILE@{ub} argument.

@{b}\\guidepath@{ub} : Path of the guide file, as given on the command line.

@{b}\\guideabspath@{ub} : Absolute path of the guide.

@{b}\\currentnodenumber@{ub}  :  This is a counter containing the node number. Set by
the default @{b}\\node@{ub} macro.

@{b}\\currentnodetitle@{ub}  :  Title  of  the current node. Set by the default \\node
macro.

@{b}\\titlepagehead@{ub},      @{b}\\titlepagefoot@{ub},      @{b}\\leftpagehead@{ub},     @{b}\\leftpagefoot@{ub},
@{b}\\rightpagehead@{ub},  @{b}\\rightpagefoot@{ub}  :  contain the tokens corresponding to the
arguments with the same names.

@{b}\\titlepage@{ub}  is  a  new  if.  Set  @{b}\\titlepagetrue@{ub}  if  you want a page to be
considered  as a title page (that is @{b}\\titlepagehead@{ub} and @{b}\\titlepagefoot@{ub} will
be  inserted  in  place  of @{b}\\left(right)pagehead@{ub} and @{b}\\left(right)pagefoot)@{ub}.
This  remains  active  only  for one page and is false (@{b}\\titlepagefalse@{ub}) by
default.

@{b}\\authordef@{ub} is a new if. It is true (\\authordeftrue) if a \@author command has been found
in the guide, in which case the @{b}\\author@{ub} token is defined.

@{b}\\author@{ub} contains the name of the author of the guide, if @{b}\\authordef@{ub} is true
(test  it with a command like @{i}"\\ifauthordef author:\\the\\author\\else unknown
author"@{ui}).

@{b}\\guideversiondef@{ub}  is  a  new  if which is true if a \@$VER: command has been
found in the guide, in which case @{b}\\guideversion@{ub} is defined.

@{b}\\guideversion@{ub}  contains  the  version  message  of the guide. Only valid if
@{b}\\guideversiondef@{ub} is true (see \\author above).

@{b}\\cpyrghtdef@{ub}  is  a  new  if  set to true if a \@(c) command was found in the
guide, in which case @{b}\\cpyrght@{ub} is defined.

@{b}\\cpyrght@{ub}  contains  the  copyright  message of the guide, if defined (i.e.
@{b}\\cpyrghtdef@{ub}  is true). Make the difference between \\copyright (the © sign,
in TeX) and this token.

@{b}\\masterdef@{ub} is a new if, true if the \@master command was found in the guide. In that
case, @{b}\\master@{ub} is defined.

@{b}\\master@{ub}  contains  the name of the file used for the creation of the guide.
Rarely used in practice. Only valid if @{b}\\masterdef@{ub} is true.


Finally,  those macros are used, you can redefine them in a @{b}PREINCLUDE@{ub} file
for a different look of the converted file:

@{b}\\link#1@{ub}  : This is the macro called for each link found. The argument #1 is
the text of the link. The default is \\underbar{#1} (underlines the link).

@{b}\\node#1#2@{ub}  :  This  is the macro called when a new node is encountered. The
arguments  #1 and #2 are respectively the number of the node and its title.
The   default   is   {\\bf  #1.---  #2}\\medskip\\nobreak\\currentnodenumber=#1
\\currentnodetitle={#2}  (prints in bold the node number, a dot, an em dash,
the  node  title, skips a medium vertical space, prevents a page break, and
sets  the @{b}\\currentnodenumber@{ub} and @{b}\\currentnodetitle@{ub} values). Remember to set
these  last two tokens if you use them elsewhere (e.g. in the head/footline
of a page).

@{b}\\endnode@{ub}  : This is the macro called when the end of a node is reached. The
default  is  \\smallskip\\hrule\\goodbreak\\bigskip which does a small vertical
skip,  draws  a  horizontal line, indicates the possibility of a page break
and does a big vertical skip.

@{b}\\gobold@{ub},  @{b}\\gounbold@{ub},  @{b}\\goitalic@{ub},  @{b}\\gounitalic@{ub}, @{b}\\gounderline@{ub}, @{b}\\goununderline@{ub}
are  macros called when a style change is required. See @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex} for
the  default  values. They are there for an easy redefinition, they are not
really used by GuideToDVI.rexx, rather by @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex}.

@{b}\\blanklineskip@{ub}  :  this  macro is inserted when a blank line is detected in
the  guide. See @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex} for a description, as this macro is used as
the  @{b}BLANKLINESKIP@{ub}  argument  for  @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex}.  The  default  value is
\\medskip.
@endnode

@node readargs "ReadArgs() conventions"
@{b}/A@{ub} denotes a mandatory argument. If it is not given, the program will fail.

@{b}/K@{ub}  indicates  that  the  keyword  must  be  explicitely  specified for the
argument  to  be  recognized.  You can use a space or an = sign between the
keyword and the argument.

@{b}/N@{ub} says that the argument must be a number.

@{b}/S@{ub} says the argument is a switch: either it is present or it is not.

@{b}/T@{ub}  says  the argument is a toggle. You can use either the argument name to
flip the swich on or off or use the name followed by on or off. This way an
argument may be set several times (on the command line or a config file).

@{u}Note@{uu} :   The    ARexx    implementation    of    ReadArgs()   is   in   the
rexxdossupport.library by Hartmut Goebel. Great work, Hartmut.
@endnode

@node provheaders "Provided header files"
This  release of GuideToTeX contains only two header files. Hopefully there
will  be more in the future. If you write interesting ones, send them to @{"me" link contact}
so that I can include them in the next release.

Headers  are  used  with the @{b}PREINCLUDE@{ub} option of either @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex} or
@{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi}. They add further features for the layout.

@{i}TitlePage.tex@{ui}:
	This file is my first attempt at creating an automatic title page
generator. Use it (only) with @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi}:

@{i}RX GuideToDVI <AmigaGuidefile> PRE TitlePage.tex@{ui}

This  will result in a title page being created with the database name in a
box  in  the  middle  of  the  page,  and  author,  copyright  and  version
information  if  defined (see @{"GuideToDVI" link guidetodvi}), a blank page right after it. Try
it.

@{i}BoxLinks.tex@{ui}
	This  renders  links  as  boxes (just like in Multiview) instead of
underlining them. The printed result is not that good, that's why I did not
make  it  the  default.  But  if you like it, use it as the @{b}PRE@{ub} argument in
@{"GuideToDVI" link guidetodvi}.
@endnode

@node FAQ "FAQs and hints"
In  this  section,  I've  put  some hints and FAQs about the conversion and
typesetting  via  GuideToTeX  of  an  AmigaGuide® file. If you have further
problems not listed here or in @{"known problems" link probs}, mail @{"me" link contact}.

@{i}When  typesetting,  TeX   complains about many overfull boxes and there are
black boxes in the right margin.@{ui}

	This  is  not the fault of GuideToTeX, rather that of TeX, which is
kind  of  picky about a line running into the right margin. The solution is
to  reformat  the  guide  file and add spaces where you can tolerate a line
break. If this still isn't sufficient, you may have to edit the TeX file to
instruct manually what to do to TeX.
	If  the  overfull  amount is small and you can tolerate it, you may
ignore the message and use the @{b}BLACKBOXES off@{ub} option of @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi}. Or
you  can increase the tolerance of TeX by modifying the @{i}\\hfuzz@{ui} value (which
is  set  at  the  beginning  of the document to 1pt by @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi} (not
@{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex}!).  If  this  still  isn't  enough,  you  can  insert  some
@{i}\\goodbreak@{ui} macros where the lines can be broken, or maybe a @{i}\\raggedright@{ui} to
tell TeX to abandon the right justification.


@{i}What should I do with underfull boxes?@{ui}

	Ignore them, in most cases.


@{i}I  get  messages "warning, untranslated non-ASCII character". What should I
do?@{ui}

	TeX  only  works  with @{b}ASCII@{ub} characters (ie whose code is between 0
and  127)  as  the  other  ones  (128-255)  are  not  completely  standard.
GuideToTeX  does its best to convert @{b}Latin-1@{ub} characters (such as those used
by  the  Amiga,  Unix,  and  er...  Widnoze? Whats the name of that DOS-GUI
again?  :-)  )  to valid TeX macros, but this is not always possible. It is
easy  to do so for accented letters, I did not always find a equivalent for
the  others.  One  of the hardest ones was the "registered" logo ®, but the
result is quite good I think. Currently, supported characters are:

Ŕ Á Ĺ Ă Ä Ĺ Ć Ç Č É Ę Ë Ě Í Î Ď Ń Ň Ó Ô Ő Ö Ů Ú Ű Ü Ý ß ŕ á â ă ä ĺ ć ç č é
ę ë ě í î ď ń ň ó ô ő ö ÷ ř ů ú ű ü ý ˙ × Ř   ˇ © « » ¬ ­ ° ± ˛ ł µ ¶ · ¸ ą
Ľ ˝ ľ ż ®

If you have suggestions for the other ones, let @{"me" link contact} know so I can update the
translation  routine.  In  the  meantime,  when  GuideToTeX  encounters  an
untranslatable  character, it warns the user and includes the character "as
is"  in  the  TeX file. Most of the time, unless you use a 8-bit version of
TeX  (most  are nowadays) AND the involved character is defined as a macro,
it is ignored by TeX's typesetting algorithm.

	If   you  know  your  guide  file  does  only  contain  pure  ASCII
characters, you can disable the translation routine in @{"GuideToTeX.rexx" link guidetotex} with
the  @{b}NOACCENTS@{ub}  keyword.  This is not possible for @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi} for now,
@{"let me know" link contact} if it is a problem.


@{i}How can I include several header or post-include files?@{ui}

	This  is  only  possible  for  @{"GuideToDVI.rexx" link guidetodvi}.  You  must edit the
configuration  file  and  add  a  line with the @{b}PREINCLUDE@{ub} (or @{b}POSTINCLUDE@{ub})
argument  and the corresponding file name. You can put as many as you wish,
but  always on a different line. Be warned that you can put only one on the
command line.


@{i}"Manually" underlined section titles appear strangely in the TeX file...@{ui}

	Many  people  use  a  row  of  dashes or asterisks or other strange
characters  to underline or draw a box around important text. Unfortunately
there  is  no  real means to track this and, even if GuideToTeX will gladly
convert  those  characters, the result in TeX won't be as good as expected,
as TeX treats carriage returns as spaces. Even with an \obeylines macro, be
sure  that ASCII art and TeX don't go well together. Then again, neither do
ASCII  art  and  proportionnal  fonts.  The only thing to do is to manually
remove those underliners from the TeX source before re-typesetting.
@endnode

@node hist "History"
@{u}Version 1.01 (27.10.98)@{uu}
	Fixed  the  way ^ and ~ are converted. It should work now (reported
by Himanshu Gohel).
	A space was missing after the conversion of ĺ and Ĺ.
	Updated the FAQs.
	Updated my e-mail address.

@{u}Version 1.0 (10.08.98)@{uu}
	Added  an  empty  group {} after an \hskip command so that indented
lines begining with "plus" aren't misinterpreted.
	Modified  the  way  inclusions  are  made  in GuideToDVI.rexx: line
\\input  instead of a brutal inclusion, but the file management in TeX is so
lousy  that  it couldn't find half of the files. I reverted to the "brutal"
way. It works :-).
	Now  a  kludge in the GuideToDVI configuration file reading routine
allows  for  several PRE/POST arguments, although ReadArgs() does not allow
/K/M.  Note  however  that you MUST write each such argument on a different
configuration file line.
	The commands \@author, \@$ver:, \@(c), \@master are now known.
	Added an Argue GUI for GuideToDVI.rexx.

@{u}Version 1.0 beta (03.08.98)@{uu}
	First internal version.
@endnode

@node probs "Known problems"
This is a list of known problems. Work is on the way to correct them.

---  Problems  with  mixed  styles:  unbold  also cancels italic and so on.
However  this  could  be  fixed  by  the  use  of a bit of TeX conditionnal
programming. I'll think of it.

---  Some guides use a non-zero left margin, which cause a new paragraph in
the  TeX  file.  In future versions I might add a workaround for this, with
maybe a real support for hanging indentation.

--- Still there are some AmigaGuide commands that could be exploited, but I
had to begin somewhere.

--- No real index support. This would be @{b}VERY@{ub} hard to implement. :-)

---  It's  slow.  Yes  I  know it. When I have some time I @{b}might@{ub} work out a
compiled version!

If you discover bugs or would like enhancements, @{"mail" link contact} me!!
@endnode

@node contact "Contacting the author"
For  everything  about  Amiga, Maths, bug reports, or a little chat, do not
hesitate to mail me:

@{u}e-mail@{uu}: Frederic.Delacroix\@univ-valenciennes.fr

@{u}Snail-mail@{uu}:
	Frédéric Delacroix
	4 rue Mirland
	59300 Valenciennes
	France.

GuideToTeX  was  written  and  tested  on an A1200 equipped with a Blizzard
1230IV  SCSI-2 turbo board, a 405Mb IDE HD and 8Mb of FAST memory. Being an
ARexx  program,  I  really  see no reason why it should fail due to another
configuration... unless you use Widows, of course :-)
@endnode

